\f2\fs24 \cf0 \
Bricksmith is a 3D model-making application designed to make it easy to create instructions for your Lego models. Best of all, you can never run out of bricks!\
\
\

\f0\b\fs26 Getting Started
\f2\b0\fs24 \
First of all, you need Mac OS X 10.3 (Panther) or later.\
\
Bricksmith is based on the LDraw library, a fan-driven project to model virtual Lego-brand building bricks. You must have a copy of the LDraw library in order to use this program. If you downloaded the complete Bricksmith package, this step is already done. Otherwise, please visit \cf2 www.ldraw.org\cf0  and follow the Macintosh instructions.\
\
Once you have LDraw, open Bricksmith. If it can't find your LDraw folder, it will ask you where it is. If you goof up somehow, just go to the preferences and choose it there.\
\
\

\f0\b\fs26 Model-Making: The Basics
\f2\b0\fs24 \
Select parts from the 
\f3\b Part Browser
\f2\b0  drawer, where you get a small preview of each part. If you despise drawers, close the Part Browser and go to Model
\f4 \'ae
\f2 \cf0 Insert Part, and you'll get a nice resizable dialog.\
\
Once you have a part selected in your model, move it with the arrow keys. Hold down the option key to move along the third axis. There are also toolbar buttons to move\cf0  and rotate.\
\

\f5\i The Inspector: 
\f2\i0 For power editing, go to Tools
\f4 \'ae
\f2 \cf0 Show Info and bask in the glow of a rich inspector, where you can futz with every available attribute of whatever you have selected. Take note; this will figure prominently in later examples.\
\cf0 \
Have Fun!\
\

\f0\b\fs26 Making Instructions: Models, Steps, MPD, etc.
\f2\b0\fs24 \
Lego creations are all about the steps required to make them. You'll find a hierarchical view of your Bricksmith creation by choosing Tools
\f4 \'ae
\f2 File Contents, organized into models, steps, and parts.\
\
\pard\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\li540\ql\qnatural

\f0\b\fs26 \cf0 Models
\f2\b0\fs24 \
LDraw files can contain more than one model. (This is referred to as 
\f5\i MPD
\f2\i0 , for Multi-Part Document.) You add models to your project by choosing Model
\f4 \'ae
\f2 Add Model. You should then open the inspector on the model and give it a name and some other information. You can then add parts to the new model to your heart's content. To switch between models, you can choose their names from the list at the bottom of the models menu.\
\
\pard\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\li540\ql\qnatural

\f5\i \cf0 How to add one model to another model: 
\f2\i0 Let's say you've built a lovely submodel named "Joe Vig" (everybody's favorite minifigure) and you've also built another lovely submodel called "Disaster at the Well," a small vignette. Now you want to put Joe in the vignette where he belongs. I'm afraid I didn't make it particularly straightforward. \
